        <div class="article-tags">
          {tags.map(tag => (
            <span class="tag">{tag}</span>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </header>

    <!-- ARTICLE CONTENT -->
    <div class="article-content">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="content-wrapper">
          <div class="post-content">
            <h2>Introduction</h2>
            <p>Behaviour support can be a valuable service for NDIS participants, but knowing when to engage a behaviour support practitioner isn't always clear. Here are five key signs that suggest behaviour support might be beneficial:</p>

            <h2>1. Difficulty Achieving NDIS Goals Due to Behaviours</h2>
            <p>If behaviours of concern are consistently preventing progress toward NDIS goals, behaviour support can help identify triggers and develop strategies to address these barriers. This might include:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Difficulty participating in community activities</li>
              <li>Challenges with daily living skills development</li>
              <li>Barriers to employment or education goals</li>
              <li>Social inclusion challenges</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>2. Increased Restrictive Practices or Crisis Situations</h2>
            <p>Frequent use of restrictive practices or regular crisis situations indicate that proactive behaviour support strategies could help reduce the need for such interventions. Watch for:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Regular use of physical intervention</li>
              <li>Frequent emergency service calls</li>
              <li>Repeated placement breakdowns</li>
              <li>High staff turnover due to challenging behaviours</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>3. Support Team Stress and Inconsistency</h2>
            <p>When support workers or family members express stress, uncertainty, or inconsistency in responding to behaviours, professional behaviour support can provide clarity and unified approaches:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Staff requesting additional training or support</li>
              <li>Inconsistent responses across team members</li>
              <li>High staff turnover or burnout</li>
              <li>Family members feeling overwhelmed</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>4. Quality of Life Concerns</h2>
            <p>If behaviours are limiting community participation, relationships, or daily activities, behaviour support can help develop strategies to improve overall quality of life:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Social isolation or withdrawal</li>
              <li>Limited community access</li>
              <li>Difficulty maintaining relationships</li>
              <li>Reduced independence in daily activities</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>5. Transition or Change-Related Challenges</h2>
            <p>Major life transitions often trigger increased support needs where behaviour support can provide stability:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Moving to new accommodation</li>
              <li>Changing service providers</li>
              <li>Staff turnover or roster changes</li>
              <li>Life stage transitions (school to adult services)</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>What to Do Next</h2>
            <p>If you recognize any of these signs, consider reaching out for an initial consultation. Behaviour support works best when implemented proactively rather than waiting for crisis situations.</p>

            <h2>Early Intervention Benefits</h2>
            <p>Engaging behaviour support early can prevent issues from escalating, reduce the need for restrictive practices, and improve outcomes for everyone involved. Don't wait until crisis point - early intervention is key to success.</p>

            <h2>Next Steps</h2>
            <p>Ready to explore behaviour support options? <a href="/contact">Contact me</a> for a free initial consultation to discuss your specific situation and how behaviour support might help.</p>
          </div>

          <!-- AUTHOR BIO -->
          <div class="author-bio">
            <div class="bio-header">
              <h3>About the Author</h3>
            </div>
            <div class="bio-content">
              <div class="bio-photo">
                <img src="/images/headshot.jpg" alt="Syed Bokhari" />
              </div>
              <div class="bio-text">
